						<div class="elementor-element elementor-element-9879945 elementor-position-left elementor-vertical-align-top elementor-widget elementor-widget-image-box" data-id="9879945" data-element_type="widget" data-widget_type="image-box.default">
				<div class="elementor-widget-container">
					<div class="elementor-image-box-wrapper"><figure class="elementor-image-box-img"><a href="https://scholars.duke.edu/person/alberto" tabindex="-1"><img decoding="async" width="296" height="300" src="https://cryoem.cs.duke.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/alberto-345-x-350-296x300.jpg" class="elementor-animation-grow attachment-medium size-medium wp-image-1439" alt="" srcset="https://cryoem.cs.duke.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/alberto-345-x-350-296x300.jpg 296w, https://cryoem.cs.duke.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/alberto-345-x-350-300x305.jpg 300w, https://cryoem.cs.duke.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/alberto-345-x-350-100x100.jpg 100w, https://cryoem.cs.duke.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/alberto-345-x-350.jpg 400w" sizes="(max-width: 296px) 100vw, 296px" /></a></figure><div class="elementor-image-box-content"><h3 class="elementor-image-box-title"><a href="https://scholars.duke.edu/person/alberto">Alberto Bartesaghi, PhD (Associate Professor)</a></h3><p class="elementor-image-box-description">Alberto received his PhD in Electrical and Computer Engineering from the University of Minnesota in 2005. He was an Associate Scientist at the National Cancer Institute at the National Institutes of Health, Bethesda, MD between 2005 and 2018 and became an Associate Professor of Computer Science and Biochemistry at Duke University in 2018. His lab develops computational methods to solve the structure of large macromolecular complexes by single particle cryo-electron microscopy, cryo-electron tomography and sub-volume averaging. He is also interested more broadly in machine learning, computer vision, image processing, and high-performance computing.</p></div></div>				</div>
